3 async function
The async and await keywords enable asynchronous, promise-based behavior to be written in a cleaner style, avoiding the need to explicitly configure promise chains.

The async function declaration declares an async function where the await keyword is used within the function body.



App.js

async function greet() {
  return 'Hello, world!';
}

async function main() {
  const message = await greet();
  console.log(message);
}

main();



In this example, the greet function is an async function that returns a promise that resolves to the string ‚ÄúHello, world!‚Äù. The main function is also an async function that calls the greet function and waits for the promise to resolve using the await keyword. When the promise resolves, the value is assigned to the message variable and logged to the console.
Async functions can contain zero or more await expressions. Await expressions make promise-returning functions behave as though they‚Äôre synchronous by suspending execution until the returned promise is fulfilled or rejected.
The resolved value of the promise is treated as the return value of the await expression. Use of async and await enables the use of ordinary try / catch blocks around asynchronous code.


App.js

function resolveAfter2Seconds() {
  return new Promise(resolve => {
    setTimeout(() => {
      resolve('resolved');
    }, 2000);
  });
}

async function asyncCall() {
  console.log('calling');
  const result = await resolveAfter2Seconds();
  console.log(result);
  // expected output: "resolved"
}

asyncCall();

